{"title":{"rendered":"Primitive Huts"},"content":{"rendered":"<figure id=\"attachment_6019\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-6019\" src=\"https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223038/primitivehuts_Page_6.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"2048\" height=\"2829\" srcset=\"https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223038/primitivehuts_Page_6.jpg 2048w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223038/primitivehuts_Page_6-217x300.jpg 217w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223038/primitivehuts_Page_6-768x1061.jpg 768w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223038/primitivehuts_Page_6-741x1024.jpg 741w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223038/primitivehuts_Page_6-1200x1658.jpg 1200w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 1362px) 62vw, 840px\" /><figcaption class=\"wp-caption-text\">Jingqiu Zhang + Baolin Shen<br />The drawing is a collage of a series of impressions about hutong. It intends to depict the behavior patterns of the residents and objects in the place. “Primitive hut,” in this case, is not a building, but an inverted situation, a void that is defined by community interrelations. Instead of using plan, bird’s-eye view or axonometric, we chose human perspective to describe the experience of walking.</figcaption></figure>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_6018\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-6018\" src=\"https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223035/primitivehuts_Page_5.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"2048\" height=\"1601\" srcset=\"https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223035/primitivehuts_Page_5.jpg 2048w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223035/primitivehuts_Page_5-300x234.jpg 300w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223035/primitivehuts_Page_5-768x600.jpg 768w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223035/primitivehuts_Page_5-1024x800.jpg 1024w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223035/primitivehuts_Page_5-1200x938.jpg 1200w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 1362px) 62vw, 840px\" /><figcaption class=\"wp-caption-text\">Iro Karavela<br />Caves were the first homes of people, a perfect shelter from the weather and the danger of wild animals. The stable temperatures provided a cool habitat in summers and a warm, dry shelter in the winter. Caves were also used as places of worship and burial. Especially during war and other times of strife, relatively small groups of people have lived temporarily in caves. Formations of land produce enough space for design orientations.</figcaption></figure>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_6017\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-6017\" src=\"https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223032/primitivehuts_Page_4.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1152\" height=\"1152\" srcset=\"https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223032/primitivehuts_Page_4.jpg 1152w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223032/primitivehuts_Page_4-150x150.jpg 150w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223032/primitivehuts_Page_4-300x300.jpg 300w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223032/primitivehuts_Page_4-768x768.jpg 768w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223032/primitivehuts_Page_4-1024x1024.jpg 1024w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 1362px) 62vw, 840px\" /><figcaption class=\"wp-caption-text\">Humans of the early millennial period were known to occupy InstaHuts, or iHuts, basic shelters made of LED panels that glowed at night with live streams of rendered architectural images. An operable roof allowed for periodic air exchange and improved WiFi signal. Anthropologists suspect that the size of the iHut may have been determined by that of the human in fetal position, a bodily format assumed for the nightly ritual of “bedtime scroll.”</figcaption></figure>\n<figure id=\"attachment_6016\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-6016\" src=\"https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223030/primitivehuts_Page_3.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1397\" height=\"1977\" srcset=\"https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223030/primitivehuts_Page_3.jpg 1397w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223030/primitivehuts_Page_3-212x300.jpg 212w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223030/primitivehuts_Page_3-768x1087.jpg 768w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223030/primitivehuts_Page_3-724x1024.jpg 724w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223030/primitivehuts_Page_3-1200x1698.jpg 1200w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 1362px) 62vw, 840px\" /><figcaption class=\"wp-caption-text\">Eduardo Mouhtar Rafeh<br />If all buildings are truly descendant from Laugier’s hut, then it could only mean that the notion, “vernacular” transcends the formal, and aesthetic arguments, and revolves around a more sincere response to the particular relations between man and his most basic needs. For that matter, today’s primitive hut is closer to an informal settlement’s house made from brick and zinc, than to any other obscure premise. Today’s primitive hut is still the need for shelter.</figcaption></figure>\n<figure id=\"attachment_6015\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-6015\" src=\"https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223028/primitivehuts_Page_2.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"2048\" height=\"2861\" srcset=\"https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223028/primitivehuts_Page_2.jpg 2048w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223028/primitivehuts_Page_2-215x300.jpg 215w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223028/primitivehuts_Page_2-768x1073.jpg 768w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223028/primitivehuts_Page_2-733x1024.jpg 733w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223028/primitivehuts_Page_2-1200x1676.jpg 1200w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 1362px) 62vw, 840px\" /><figcaption class=\"wp-caption-text\">Dominique Cheng<br />What is it made of? Soft, durable fabric; shapeable. How is it built? Conventional binding, stitching, hemming, pleating, and ruching for structural integrity. Who and What is it for? A loner; nomad with no material possessions; for solitary confinement or meditation.</figcaption></figure>\n<figure id=\"attachment_6014\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-6014\" src=\"https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223025/primitivehuts_Page_1.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1278\" height=\"810\" srcset=\"https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223025/primitivehuts_Page_1.jpg 1278w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223025/primitivehuts_Page_1-300x190.jpg 300w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223025/primitivehuts_Page_1-768x487.jpg 768w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223025/primitivehuts_Page_1-1024x649.jpg 1024w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31223025/primitivehuts_Page_1-1200x761.jpg 1200w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 1362px) 62vw, 840px\" /><figcaption class=\"wp-caption-text\">The building on the corner made of blue advertisements.</figcaption></figure>\n<figure id=\"attachment_5985\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-5985\" src=\"https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31221545/Serena-Ching.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1824\" height=\"1176\" srcset=\"https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31221545/Serena-Ching.jpg 1824w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31221545/Serena-Ching-300x193.jpg 300w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31221545/Serena-Ching-768x495.jpg 768w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31221545/Serena-Ching-1024x660.jpg 1024w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31221545/Serena-Ching-1200x774.jpg 1200w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 1362px) 62vw, 840px\" /><figcaption class=\"wp-caption-text\">Serena Ching<br />Multifamily Iban longhouse [rumah panjang] in Sarawak, Malaysia.</figcaption></figure>\n<figure id=\"attachment_5986\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-5986\" src=\"https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31221549/shed.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"1891\" height=\"2780\" srcset=\"https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31221549/shed.png 1891w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31221549/shed-204x300.png 204w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31221549/shed-768x1129.png 768w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31221549/shed-697x1024.png 697w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31221549/shed-1200x1764.png 1200w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 1362px) 62vw, 840px\" /><figcaption class=\"wp-caption-text\">Rukshan the 27th<br />Shed</figcaption></figure>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<figure id=\"attachment_5987\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-5987\" src=\"https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31221551/WarrenOhio.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1741\" height=\"816\" srcset=\"https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31221551/WarrenOhio.jpg 1741w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31221551/WarrenOhio-300x141.jpg 300w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31221551/WarrenOhio-768x360.jpg 768w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31221551/WarrenOhio-1024x480.jpg 1024w, https://d2rpbtor0vesnk.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/31221551/WarrenOhio-1200x562.jpg 1200w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 709px) 85vw, (max-width: 909px) 67vw, (max-width: 1362px) 62vw, 840px\" /><figcaption class=\"wp-caption-text\">My Primitive Hut, Warren, Ohio.</figcaption></figure>\n"},"meta":{"fold":{"title":{"rendered":"&#8220;Vernacular&#8221;"},"slug":"vernacular","meta":{"volume":"04","number":"06","bulletin":false,"publication_date":"2018-11-01"}}}}